<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Stagecoach Group plc (LTD0018)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Stagecoach Group plc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (LTD0018)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">INTRODUCTION</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is the response by Stagecoach Group plc to the Transport Committee new inquiry call for evidence on Local Decision Making on Transport Expenditure. As rail expenditure is largely controlled through national funding, our response relates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to expenditure on local bus services.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stagecoach would wish to see greater guidance from national government to ensure that LEPs and LTBs have more balanced representation of public transport interests in their membership.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stagecoach woul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d wish to see greater guidance from national government to ensure that LEPs and LTBs have a more balanced mix of spending projects between road capacity and public transport.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stagecoach would wish to see new guidance from national government to LEPs and LT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Bs to consider revenue expenditure on public transport projects on the same cost benefit terms as capital projects.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DEVOLUTION</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As part of its localism agenda national government has replaced regional government with Local Enterprise Partnerships, with spen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ding on major transport schemes to be determined by Local Transport Bodies.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local Enterprise Partnerships are unelected bodies comprising members representing local government, public and private businesses and community groups. The boundaries of LEPs have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been decided locally, resulting in a wide variety of size from single county council to multi council and in some cases overlapping areas. These are not aligned to Local Transport Authority and Integrated Transport Authority boundaries. It is unclear how </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">membership of LEPs has been decided, but few include representatives of local bus operators or passenger representative groups. Each LEP appears to have different procedures for meetings, and in some cases there appears to be little consultation with other</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> interested parties who are not members of the LEP.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local Transport Boards comprise mainly elected members of corresponding LEP areas with authority to determine spending priorities, together with LEP representatives and potentially other non-voting membe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rs. LTBs are similarly not aligned to LTA or ITA areas.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> At local level Stagecoach has found it difficult to engage with LEPs and LTBs.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stagecoach would wish to see greater guidance from national government to ensure that LEPs and LTBs have more balanced re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">presentation of public transport interests in their membership.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">SPENDING PRIORITIES</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local buses are the most used form of public transport with 4.7 billion bus trips annually, serving a wide variety of purposes including travel for work, education, sh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oppin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g and leisure. Independent research by Greener Journeys shows that:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.5m workers per day travel by bus creating £64 billion pa economic output</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.4b shopping trips pa by bus creating £27 billion pa retail spend</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">40% of high street trips made by bus compared </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with 30% by car or van</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5% of domestic CO2 emissions made by bus compared with 67% by cars and taxis</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">82% of unemployed 18-24 year olds have no access to a car</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, with little or no representation on LEPs or LTBs, bus operators and passenger representat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ives have little opportunity to present a case for public transport expenditure on bus priority schemes. The result, as demonstrated by an analysis of LTB </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">scheme priorities by Campaign for Better Transport, is a predominance of road building schemes. Bus p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rojects form only 7% of total planned expenditure. It may simply be the case that without any membership advocates of public transport, LEPs and LTBs overlook relatively low cost bus schemes in favour of larger </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and more expensive highway </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">projects.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The domi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nance of road construction </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">isks a return to the unsustainable “predict and provide” policies of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">previous century</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, with associated problems of increasing congestion and pollution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ajor Bus Rapid Transit schemes such as West Yorkshire, Cambridgeshire, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Luton &amp; Dunstable, North Kent and Gosport &amp; Fareham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and the planned Leigh-Manchester scheme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have demonstrated the ability of local buses to provide an effective and sustainable alternative to road construction. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Such schemes have been promoted by the local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> LTAs and ITAs. It is unclear how similar schemes might be promoted and prioritised in future under LEPs and LTBs.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As LEPs must submit their Strategic Economic Plans by March 2014 for the period 2015-2020, and few LEPs have considered major bus transport s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">chemes, it seems likely that few if any such schemes will become possible until at least 2021.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stagecoach would wish to see greater guidance from national government to ensure that LEPs and LTBs have a more balanced mix of spending projects between roa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d capacity and public transport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> schemes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">CAPITAL &amp; REVENUE EXPENDITURE</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The new LEP and LTB bodies are primarily concerned with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">major </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transport capital expenditure projects. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">By their nature such schemes tend to be large and expensive.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> In contrast, other tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n major BRT schemes, public transport capital expenditure projects such as bus priorities and bus shelters tend to be small in scale and value. Stagecoach is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">concerned that small scale public transport schemes may be overlooked in favour of “grand projects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Because they operate on the common road network, local buses are not heavily dependent on public capital expenditure, the vehicles being mainly financed by private capital. The majority of local bus se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rvices are operated commercially, with around 20% of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> services requiring public sector support through competitive tendering. All services benefit from national government funded Bus Service Operators Grant, and are required to carry eligible elderly and disabled passengers free of charge for which a proport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ion of the average fare is paid to operators by local government.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As part of the national economic austerity measures and public expenditure cuts, BSOG was cut by 20% in 2012 and frozen in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cash</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> terms until 2016. BSOG for tendered services has been transfer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">red from operators to local authorities, but only ring-fenced until 2016. Concession travel re-imbursement has been reduced in real terms to a level below the average cost of carriage per passenger. In addition to these factors many local authority support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed services have been reduced or withdrawn due to public spending cuts. Government policy has been to protect capital spending projects at the expense of revenue spending, and this policy has a disproportionately adverse effect on local bus services. There</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> does not appear to be any national measure to compare the cost benefit of capital</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> expenditure projects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with revenue expenditure projects, although there may be greater public benefit in continuing to support unprofitable but socially desirable local bus s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ervices rather than a new capital project.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stagecoach would wish to see new guidance from national government to LEPs and LTBs to consider revenue expenditure on public transport projects on the same cost benefit terms as capital projects.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Stagecoach Group</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stagecoach Group is a leading international public transport group, with extensive operations in the UK, United States and Canada. The Group employs around 36,000 people, and operates bus, coach, train, and tram services. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stagecoach is one of the UK’s bi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ggest bus and coach operators with around 8,000 buses and coaches. Around 2.5 million passengers travel on Stagecoach's buses every day on a network stretching from south-west England to the Highlands and Islands of Scotland. The Group’s business includes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">major city bus operations in London, Liverpool, Newcastle, Hull, Manchester, Oxford, Sheffield and Cambridge. Low-cost coach service, megabus.com, operates between around 60 towns and cities across the UK.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stagecoach is a major UK rail operator, running th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e South West Trains, Island Line and East Midlands Trains networks. It has a 49% shareholding in Virgin Rail Group, which operates the West Coast rail franchise. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Stagecoach also operates the Supertram light rail network in Sheffield.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In North America, Stagecoach operates around 2,600 buses and coaches in the United States and Canada. Megabus.com links around 100 key locations in North America. Stagecoach is also involved in operating commuter and transit services, contracted bus servic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es, charters, sightseeing tours and a small number of school bus services. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt">